      Opera onal review
    

      − USA
    

      The main drivers in 2016 have been to refocus on the core transformer oil re‐reﬁning technology by op mising the performance of the Canton facility, and to increase produc on levels through a combina on of leveraging the experience gained since fully commissioning the plant at the end of last year along with speciﬁc targeted opera ng improvements, building on lessons learned during the commissioning process. These improvements have been validated by the signiﬁcantly lower number of produc on hours lost through unscheduled stoppages and the record monthly produc on performance of the plant in May of 2.82 million litres of SUPERFINE transformer oil and base oil. Plant u lisa on increased over the period, from an average of 64% in Q1 to 70% in Q2 with a peak of 76% in May and has averaged 68% through Q3 to date.
    

      These developments have supported total sales volumes in Canton in the period of 15.5 million litres. An addi onal primary objec ve relates to improving the sales mix between higher margin transformer oil and lower margin base oil produced at the Canton plant. At the beginning of the year, January transformer oil sales represented 19% of US volumes sold. Since then signiﬁcant improvements have been made in this area and in June transformer oil represented 71% of sales, with further advances targeted. Growth in transformer oil sales have been supported by the SUPERFINE product achieving "500 hour" oil status, cer fying the oil to be high quality transformer oil and a prerequisite to accessing the larger power transformer market.
    

      Post period‐end, in September, we announced that the American Carbon Registry ("ACR") had approved Hydrodec's patented technology as a carbon oﬀset project in the voluntary carbon oﬀset market, allowing the Company to generate, and mone se, carbon credits. Hydrodec of North America ("HoNA") is now genera ng oﬀsets through the re‐reﬁning of used transformer oil, which would otherwise ordinarily be incinerated or disposed of in an unsustainable manner. The ACR has recognised 165,000 credits for HoNA's previous produc on between 2009 and 2014 and the Company an cipates that it will generate 50,000 to 60,000 tons of carbon oﬀset annually going forward. Whilst the historical credits may only generate nominal sums through trading, the ongoing genera on of such credits could realise up to US$5 per ton (source: Carbonomics).
    



          Australia
        

          In respect of the opera ons in Australia, since the commissioning of the plant at the Southern Oil Reﬁnery in May 2015 we have had to work hard to re‐establish our commercial posi on in the market. Total sales volumes in Australia for the period were 1.3 million. In May, the Australian business enjoyed one of its highest feedstock acquisi on months since 2012 and since then has consistently sourced feedstock at an op mal level to maximise its proﬁtability going forward. The focus is now on expanding the customer base and increasing the propor on of transformer oil sales.
        

          Post period‐end, in August, we announced the award of a 5 year contract to supply SUPERFINE transformer oil to Essen al Energy, a major Australian u lity. The contract includes the collec on and re‐reﬁning of all their PCB and non‐PCB waste oils and is expected to generate over 1 million litres of new transformer oil sales over the life of the contract. The contract was awarded under a compe ve tender process, with the Company successfully compe ng against a range of new oil suppliers.
        



          Market background
        



      In the US, leading producers of naphthenic speciality products, of which Hydrodec is one, have experienced lower margins due to high value inventory and lagging market prices from the impact of the ﬁrst quarter crude price fall. Whilst the Group has been successful in improving margins since the ﬁrst quarter, the Board expects margins to remain challenging for the second half of the year before improving into 2017, driven by improving product prices which lag recent increases in crude prices.
    

      In Australia, market demand and margin remain rela vely stable and the key to margin and volume improvement will be based around leveraging the award of the Essen al Energy contract to increase sales of transformer oil into the key u li es.
    

      Financial review
    

      Revenues from con nuing opera ons increased 148% to US$8.1 million (H1 2015: US$3.3 million), reﬂec ng the full commissioning of the Canton plant at the end of last year. The Group sold 16.8 million litres during the period, an increase of 217% on the corresponding period in 2015 which had included 3.6 million litres of traded oil whilst the US business was being recommissioned. Of the volumes sold in the period, 40% represented transformer oil and 60% was base oil, with margins steadily improving since the beginning of the year.
    

      There has been a key focus on the reduc on of overheads and corporate costs. Signiﬁcant reduc ons have already been realised with the expecta on that the beneﬁts from more recently implemented ini a ves will ﬁlter through in H2. These savings are reﬂected in the reduc on in administra ve expenses from con nuing opera ons from US$6.1 million to US$3.9 million as highlighted below.
    

      Six months
    

      ended
    

      Six months
    

      ended
    

      30 June 2016 30 June 2015


      USD'000 USD'000 % change


      Indirect opera ng costs (1,530) (2,824) (46%)
    

Corporate costs (1,451) (2,087) (30%) Deprecia on and amor sa on ‐ overheads (939) (1,171) (20%) Administra ve expenses (3,920) (6,082) (36%) 
    

      Group EBITDA from con nuing opera ons improved from US$3.4 million loss (H1 2015) to US$1.1 million loss. The total loss for the period (including discon nued opera ons) was US$5.3 million (H1 2015: US$8.4 million).
    

      Opera ng cash ou low (before working capital movements) reduced to US$2.0 million (H1 2015: US$5.8 million). The improved EBITDA performance resulted in lower working capital ou lows which reduced from $3.0 million to $2.4 million. Total net cash expended in the ﬁrst six months of 2016 was US$0.2 million compared to a US$12.6 million ou low in the prior year comparable period. Overall, the Group held US$0.6 million in cash on its balance sheet at the end of the period and retained approximately US$1.4 million headroom under its working capital facili es provided by Andrew Black, a Director and the Company's largest shareholder.
    

      Disposal of UK recycling opera ons
    

      In late 2015 and January 2016, the Company undertook a detailed strategic review of its UK waste oil collec ons business and proposed UK lubricant oil re‐reﬁning project, following a signiﬁcant deteriora on in its UK opera ons. This deteriora on was driven predominately by the rapid decline in global oil prices and con nued challenging market condi ons which resulted in the UK business genera ng an increasing level of signiﬁcant losses. Despite implemen ng extensive restructuring and cost‐saving measures during 2015, Hydrodec remained exposed to the impact of the global oil price decline. Given the signiﬁcant cash consump on and limited cash resources available to the Company (in the absence of a signiﬁcant further fundraising), the Directors
    

      reviewed all available op ons and concluded that it was in the best interests of the Company to dispose of the UK opera ons.
    

      Following a strategic auc on process conducted by an independent third party ﬁnancial adviser, the Company sold its UK opera ons to Andrew Black, a non‐execu ve Director and substan al shareholder (the "Buyer"), on 4 March 2016 for a considera on of £1 in cash, including the transfer to the Buyer of c. £1.2 million of exis ng third party indebtedness in the UK business and involving the injec on by the Buyer of further working capital into that opera on. In addi on, the Buyer granted Hydrodec a contractual right to receive a propor on of the Buyer's en tlement to any future proﬁts of the UK re‐reﬁning project on the following waterfall basis (a) ﬁrst, the Buyer, as primary risk taker, to recover the costs of its investment in the UK re‐reﬁning project; (b) then, the next tranche to be applied 70:30 between Hydrodec and the Buyer respec vely un l Hydrodec has recovered its costs incurred to date in connec on with the UK re‐reﬁning project; and (c) ﬁnally, the balance of any proﬁts to be shared 90:10 between the Buyer and Hydrodec. The Buyer will bear all risk and responsibility for developing the UK lubricant oil re‐reﬁning project going forward, with Hydrodec retaining only a passive economic interest under these proﬁt share arrangements. The UK re‐reﬁning project also oﬀers a poten al opportunity to develop transformer oil re‐reﬁning capacity in the UK. The impact on the Company of all of the above is described in note 12 to the interim ﬁnancial statements.
    

      Risk management process
    

      The Group has policies, processes and systems in place to help iden fy, evaluate and manage risks at all levels throughout the organisa on. Risks are regularly reviewed and monitored by business unit or func onal management teams. The execu ve team review the major risks across the Group on a quarterly basis to ensure that the management of these risks has appropriate focus. The Board review these at least twice a year.
    

The principal risks that could poten ally have a signiﬁcant impact on the Group in the future are set out on pages 12 and 13 of the 2015 Annual Report. The con nued successful opera on of Canton is the key performance impera ve for the Group. The Annual Report can be downloaded at www.hydrodec.com


      Outlook
    

      Today's results conﬁrm signiﬁcant progress in the turnaround of the Company over the ﬁrst half of the year. Our key objec ve during the rest of the year is to strengthen margins as we grow market share and seek to leverage the recent carbon credit approval in the US, whilst con nuing the program of cost reduc on. Volumes and margins in Q3 to date remain consistent with Q2 and, with both opera ons now genera ng posi ve EBITDA, we con nue to make strong progress towards posi ve Group EBITDA in the second half of the year.
    

      Chris Ellis
    

      CEO
    

      16 September 2016
    

